    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Something in the lines of</p>\n<pre><code>myString.split(&quot;\\\\s+&quot;);\n</code></pre>\n<p>This groups all white spaces as a delimiter.</p>\n<p>So if I have the string:</p>\n<pre><code>&quot;Hello[space character][tab character]World&quot;\n</code></pre>\n<p>This should yield the strings <code>&quot;Hello&quot;</code> and <code>&quot;World&quot;</code> and omit the empty space between the <code>[space]</code> and the <code>[tab]</code>.</p>\n<p>As VonC pointed out, the backslash should be escaped, because Java would first try to escape the string to a special character, and send <em>that</em> to be parsed. What you want, is the literal <code>&quot;\\s&quot;</code>, which means, you need to pass <code>&quot;\\\\s&quot;</code>. It can get a bit confusing.</p>\n<p>The <code>\\\\s</code> is equivalent to <code>[ \\\\t\\\\n\\\\x0B\\\\f\\\\r]</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1247533,
      "reputation" : 11,
      "user_id" : 1208677,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d9b9a449bdbf20aa0a2989d47879b5d5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Rishabh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1208677/rishabh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1392626096,
    "last_edit_date" : 1392626096,
    "creation_date" : 1329210082,
    "answer_id" : 9274100,
    "question_id" : 225337,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Since it is a regular expression, and i'm assuming u would also not want non-alphanumeric chars like commas, dots, etc that could be surrounded by blanks (e.g. \"one , two\" should give [one][two]), it should be:</p>\n\n<pre><code>myString.split(/[\\s\\W]+/)\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
